  <content>
    <title>AWS Well-Architected Framework Checklists (2025-2026)</title>

    <summary>Actionable checklists for all six AWS Well-Architected pillars (Operational Excellence, Security, Reliability, Performance Efficiency, Cost Optimization, Sustainability) plus new-account setup baseline and pre-production readiness gates.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>The AWS Well-Architected Framework encodes lessons from thousands of production workload reviews. Checklists translate abstract pillars into concrete pass/fail items that can be integrated into CI gates, pre-launch reviews, and quarterly audits. Without a structured checklist, security and reliability gaps persist undetected until an incident.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-launch review of a new AWS workload before production traffic.</item>
        <item>Quarterly well-architected review for an existing production environment.</item>
        <item>New AWS account baseline setup for security and cost management.</item>
        <item>Post-incident review to identify which checklist items were missing.</item>
        <item>Agent-driven environment audit where each item maps to a verifiable CLI check.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Throwaway sandbox accounts where security overhead exceeds the value.</item>
        <item>Replacing a formal AWS Well-Architected Tool review for compliance documentation — use this as a working checklist alongside the official tool.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="overview-tables">
      <p>The six-pillar framework and key design principles that guide architecture decisions on AWS.</p>

      <note>The AWS Well-Architected Framework (2025-2026) defines six pillars: Operational Excellence, Security, Reliability, Performance Efficiency, Cost Optimization, and Sustainability. Each pillar has design principles and best practices that translate into the checklists below.</note>

      <note>Key design principles: (1) Stop guessing capacity — use cloud to provision exact resources needed. (2) Test at production scale — run realistic load tests. (3) Automate experimentation — use IaC to deploy/test/iterate quickly. (4) Allow evolutionary architectures — design with loosely coupled components. (5) Drive architectures using data — use monitoring and metrics for decisions.</note>
    </section>

    <section name="operational-excellence-checklist">
      <p>Operational Excellence covers organization, preparation, operation, and continuous improvement practices.</p>

      <checklist>
        <check>Document workload requirements and priorities</check>
        <check>Define team roles and responsibilities</check>
        <check>Establish runbooks for routine procedures</check>
        <check>Create playbooks for incident response</check>
        <check>Design workloads to understand state</check>
        <check>Implement observability (logs, metrics, traces)</check>
        <check>Automate deployment with IaC (CloudFormation/Terraform)</check>
        <check>Use feature flags for safe deployments</check>
        <check>Define operational health metrics</check>
        <check>Implement automated alerting</check>
        <check>Use dashboards for operational visibility</check>
        <check>Automate responses to events where possible</check>
        <check>Conduct post-incident reviews</check>
        <check>Share learnings across teams</check>
        <check>Implement improvements from learnings</check>
        <check>Regularly review and update runbooks</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="security-checklist">
      <p>Security checklist covers IAM, detection, infrastructure protection, data protection, and incident response. IAM practices are the most critical — all marked Critical must be addressed before production.</p>

      <checklist>
        <check>Enable MFA for all human users</check>
        <check>Use IAM roles instead of long-term credentials</check>
        <check>Apply least-privilege permissions</check>
        <check>Use AWS Organizations with SCPs</check>
        <check>Enable CloudTrail in all regions</check>
        <check>Protect root account with hardware MFA</check>
        <check>Review IAM Access Analyzer findings</check>
        <check>Enable AWS Security Hub</check>
        <check>Enable Amazon GuardDuty</check>
        <check>Configure AWS Config rules</check>
        <check>Set up VPC Flow Logs</check>
        <check>Enable S3 access logging</check>
        <check>Configure CloudWatch alarms for security events</check>
        <check>Use VPCs for network isolation</check>
        <check>Implement security groups with minimal access</check>
        <check>Use NACLs for subnet-level filtering</check>
        <check>Enable AWS WAF for web applications</check>
        <check>Use AWS Shield for DDoS protection</check>
        <check>Implement network segmentation</check>
        <check>Enable encryption at rest for all data stores</check>
        <check>Use TLS 1.2+ for data in transit</check>
        <check>Manage keys with AWS KMS</check>
        <check>Enable S3 bucket versioning</check>
        <check>Block public access on S3 buckets</check>
        <check>Use Secrets Manager for credentials</check>
        <check>Create incident response runbooks</check>
        <check>Conduct regular tabletop exercises</check>
        <check>Configure automated remediation</check>
        <check>Set up AWS Backup for critical data</check>
        <check>Enable cross-region replication for DR</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="reliability-checklist">
      <p>Reliability checklist covers foundations, workload architecture for loose coupling, change management, and failure management including RTO/RPO targets.</p>

      <checklist>
        <check>Set appropriate service quotas</check>
        <check>Plan network topology with redundancy</check>
        <check>Implement multi-AZ deployments</check>
        <check>Document recovery procedures</check>
        <check>Use loosely coupled dependencies</check>
        <check>Implement circuit breakers</check>
        <check>Design for graceful degradation</check>
        <check>Use async communication where appropriate</check>
        <check>Automate deployments with CI/CD</check>
        <check>Use blue-green or canary deployments</check>
        <check>Implement automated rollback</check>
        <check>Test deployments in staging environment</check>
        <check>Define RTO and RPO for workloads</check>
        <check>Implement health checks</check>
        <check>Use Auto Scaling for fault tolerance</check>
        <check>Test recovery procedures regularly</check>
        <check>Enable automated backup</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="performance-efficiency-checklist">
      <p>Performance Efficiency covers service selection, ongoing review, monitoring, and tradeoffs such as caching and read replicas.</p>

      <checklist>
        <check>Evaluate compute options (EC2, Lambda, containers)</check>
        <check>Choose appropriate storage class</check>
        <check>Select right database type for workload</check>
        <check>Consider Graviton processors (40% better price-perf)</check>
        <check>Monitor resource utilization</check>
        <check>Use Compute Optimizer recommendations</check>
        <check>Review architecture against best practices</check>
        <check>Evaluate new AWS services regularly</check>
        <check>Set up performance dashboards</check>
        <check>Configure performance alarms</check>
        <check>Use X-Ray for distributed tracing</check>
        <check>Monitor latency percentiles (p50, p95, p99)</check>
        <check>Implement caching where beneficial</check>
        <check>Use read replicas for read-heavy workloads</check>
        <check>Consider edge locations (CloudFront)</check>
        <check>Balance consistency vs availability</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="cost-optimization-checklist">
      <p>Cost Optimization covers financial management, expenditure awareness, cost-effective resource selection, demand management, and ongoing cleanup.</p>

      <checklist>
        <check>Create AWS Budgets with alerts</check>
        <check>Enable Cost Allocation Tags</check>
        <check>Assign cost ownership to teams</check>
        <check>Review Cost Explorer monthly</check>
        <check>Track cost anomalies</check>
        <check>Tag all resources for cost allocation</check>
        <check>Use AWS Cost Categories</check>
        <check>Set up cost anomaly detection</check>
        <check>Review AWS Billing dashboard regularly</check>
        <check>Use Savings Plans for predictable usage (72% savings)</check>
        <check>Use Spot Instances for fault-tolerant workloads (90% savings)</check>
        <check>Choose Graviton instances where possible (40% savings)</check>
        <check>Right-size instances with Compute Optimizer</check>
        <check>Use appropriate storage classes (S3 lifecycle policies)</check>
        <check>Implement Auto Scaling</check>
        <check>Schedule non-production resources</check>
        <check>Use Spot Instances for batch jobs</check>
        <check>Optimize data transfer costs</check>
        <check>Review and delete unused resources</check>
        <check>Identify and remove orphaned EBS volumes</check>
        <check>Release unused Elastic IPs</check>
        <check>Delete old snapshots</check>
        <check>Review and optimize reserved capacity</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="sustainability-checklist">
      <p>Sustainability pillar focuses on reducing environmental impact through efficient region selection, demand alignment, software optimization, and data lifecycle management.</p>

      <checklist>
        <check>Choose regions with lower carbon intensity</check>
        <check>Use regions closer to users</check>
        <check>Use Auto Scaling to match resources to load</check>
        <check>Schedule resources during off-hours</check>
        <check>Implement dynamic scaling policies</check>
        <check>Optimize code for efficiency</check>
        <check>Use managed services where appropriate</check>
        <check>Implement caching to reduce computation</check>
        <check>Implement data lifecycle policies</check>
        <check>Use appropriate storage tiers</check>
        <check>Delete unnecessary data</check>
        <check>Use Graviton processors (more efficient)</check>
        <check>Adopt serverless where appropriate</check>
        <check>Use latest generation instance types</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="new-account-checklist">
      <p>Baseline configuration for a new AWS account covering security, cost management, networking, and monitoring setup.</p>

      <checklist>
        <check>Enable MFA on root account</check>
        <check>Create IAM admin user (do not use root for daily work)</check>
        <check>Enable CloudTrail in all regions</check>
        <check>Enable AWS Config</check>
        <check>Enable Security Hub</check>
        <check>Enable GuardDuty</check>
        <check>Set password policy</check>
        <check>Enable Cost Explorer</check>
        <check>Create budget alerts</check>
        <check>Enable cost allocation tags</check>
        <check>Set up billing alerts</check>
        <check>Plan VPC CIDR ranges</check>
        <check>Create VPCs in required regions</check>
        <check>Set up VPC Flow Logs</check>
        <check>Configure NAT Gateways</check>
        <check>Create CloudWatch dashboards</check>
        <check>Set up SNS topics for alerts</check>
        <check>Configure alarm thresholds</check>
        <check>Enable X-Ray for tracing</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="pre-production-checklist">
      <p>Pre-production gate checklist covering security review, performance testing, reliability testing, and operational readiness.</p>

      <checklist>
        <check>IAM policies follow least privilege</check>
        <check>No hardcoded secrets in code</check>
        <check>Data encryption enabled</check>
        <check>Security groups reviewed</check>
        <check>Public access blocked on S3</check>
        <check>Load testing completed</check>
        <check>Performance baselines established</check>
        <check>Scaling policies tested</check>
        <check>Database performance validated</check>
        <check>Failure scenarios tested</check>
        <check>Recovery procedures validated</check>
        <check>Backup and restore tested</check>
        <check>Multi-AZ failover verified</check>
        <check>Monitoring dashboards created</check>
        <check>Alerts configured</check>
        <check>Runbooks documented</check>
        <check>On-call procedures established</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="iam-security-reference">
      <p>IAM security best practices reference table and shared responsibility model for quick consultation during architecture reviews.</p>

      <note>IAM Security Priority Reference: Use federation with IdP (Critical), use temporary credentials/IAM roles (Critical), require MFA (Critical), apply least-privilege permissions (Critical), rotate access keys regularly (High), protect root user credentials (Critical).</note>

      <note>Core Security Measures: Encryption at rest via KMS on S3/EBS/RDS/DynamoDB. Encryption in transit via TLS 1.2+ / HTTPS everywhere. Logging via CloudTrail, VPC Flow Logs, S3 access logs. Monitoring via Security Hub, GuardDuty, Inspector. Secrets management via Secrets Manager and Parameter Store.</note>

      <note>Shared Responsibility Model: AWS is responsible for physical security, hardware maintenance, network infrastructure, hypervisor security. Customer is responsible for IAM configuration, security groups, data encryption, application security.</note>
    </section>

